<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ptilagrostis</i> <i>kingii</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the herbaceous and subshrub layers with <i>Bistorta</i> <i>bistortoides</i>, <i>Carex</i> <i>pachystachya</i>, <i>Carex</i> <i>subnigricans</i>, <i>Danthonia</i> <i>intermedia</i>, <i>Luzula</i> <i>orestera</i>, <i>Oreostemma</i> <i>alpigenum</i>, <i>Senecio</i> <i>scorzonella</i>, <i>Trichophorum</i> <i>clementis</i> and <i>Vaccinium</i> <i>cespitosum</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Herbs < 50 cm; cover is intermittent to continuous. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Ptilagrostis kingii</i> > 5% absolute cover and > 50% relative cover in the herbaceous layer; <i>Carex aquatilis, C. nebrascensis, C. subnigricans, C. vesicaria, Deschampsia caespitosa, Eleocharis quinqueflora, Juncus nevadensis, </i>and <i>Veratrum californicum </i>usually <5% absolute cover (Potter 2005).</li>
		
		<li><i>Ptilagrostis kingii</i> ≥ 50% relative cover in herbaceous layer (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stringer meadows and stream banks. Soils are seasonally saturated and may be hummocky. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Ptilagrostis kingii</i> as a FACU plant. </div>
</div>

        
