<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ptilagrostis kingii </i>is an erect, densely tufted, perennial grass to 40 cm tall. Plants reproduce infrequently from seed when environmental conditions are favorable. Other ecological and botanical references use the names <i>Oryzopsis kingii </i>and <i>Stipa kingii </i>for the species. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Ptilagrostis kingii </i>is restricted to higher elevations in the central and southern Sierra Nevada (Hickman 1993), where it is locally common and widespread. The alliance expresses itself as almost pure stands or as a mixture of several low turf-forming grass or sedge species, collectively termed as the shorthair class (Ratliff 1982). Their position in the meadow moisture gradient is usually midway between the more regularly flooded stands of the <i>Deschampsia cespitosa </i>or <i>Carex nebrascensis </i>alliances and the drier stands of the <i>Carex filifolia </i>and <i>Carex muiriana </i>alliances. <i>P. kingii </i>stands often occur on small rises within meadows immediately adjacent to active flowing streams, and slightly above the zone of summer saturation (Sawyer and Keeler-Wolf 2007). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
